{"title_page": "Chapel of the Oblates", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n| name                 =Chapel of the Oblates\n| fullname             =\n| image                =Chapelle des Oblats (Aix-en-Provence) by Malost.JPG\n| imagesize            =\n| landscape            =\n| caption              = Facade of the Chapel of the Oblates\n| location             = Place Forbin<br/>[[Aix-en-Provence]]<br/>[[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]], [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]]\n| country              = France\n| coordinates          =\n| denomination         =[[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| tradition            =\n| membership           =\n| attendance           =\n| website              = \n| former name          =\n| bull date            =\n| founded date         =\n| founder              =\n| dedication           =\n| dedicated date       =\n| consecrated date     =\n| cult                 =\n| relics               =\n| events               =\n| past bishop          =\n| people               =\n| status               =\n| functional status    =\n| heritage designation =[[Monument historique]]\n| designated date      =\n| architect            =[[Thomas Veyrier]]<br/>[[Laurent Vallon]]\n| architectural type   =[[church architecture|church]]\n| style                =\n| groundbreaking       =\n| completed date       =1701\n| construction cost    =\n| closed date          =\n| demolished date      =\n| parish               =\n| deanery              =\n| archdeaconry         =[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aix]]\n| diocese              =\n| province             =\n| presbytery           =\n| synod                =\n| circuit              =\n| district             =\n| division             = \n| subdivision          =\n| archbishop           =[[Christophe Dufour]]\n| bishop               = \n| dean                 =\n| subdean              =\n| provost              =\n| provost-rector       =\n| viceprovost          =\n| canon                =\n| canonpastor          =\n| precentor            =\n| archdeacon           =\n| prebendary           =\n| rector               =\n| vicar                =\n| curate               =\n| priest               = \n| pastor               = \n| asstpriest           =\n| minister             =\n| assistant            =\n| honpriest            =\n| deacon               =\n| deaconness           =\n| seniorpastor         =\n| abbot                =\n| chaplain             =\n| reader               =\n| organistdom          =\n| director             =\n| organist             =\n| organscholar         =\n| chapterclerk         =\n| laychapter           =\n| warden               =\n| flowerguild          =\n| musicgroup           =\n| parishadmin          =\n| serversguild         =\n| logo                 =\n| logosize             =\n}}\nThe '''Chapel of the Oblates''' (fr: \"Chapelle des Oblats\") is a [[Roman Catholic]] chapel in [[Aix-en-Provence]]. \n\n==Location==\nIt is located on the Place Forbin, at the top of the [[Cours Mirabeau]].<ref name=\"tourism\">[http://www.aixenprovence.fr/Chapelle-des-Oblats Aix-en-Provence Tourism: Chapelle des Oblats]</ref><ref name=\"official\">[http://www.centremazenod.org/?lang=en Official website]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe chapel was built on a former convent for the [[Carmelites]], a Roman Catholic order, built in 1625.<ref name=\"tourism\"/><ref name=\"moines\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.moinesdiocesains-aix.cef.fr/dans-la-ville/les-peres-oblats.html |title=Moines |access-date=2013-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225110225/http://www.moinesdiocesains-aix.cef.fr/dans-la-ville/les-peres-oblats.html |archive-date=2013-12-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The new chapel building was designed by [[Thomas Veyrier]] (1658-1736) and constructed from 1695 to 1701.<ref name=\"tourism\"/> The facade was designed by [[Laurent Vallon]] (1652-1724) in 1697.<ref name=\"tourism\"/> \n\nIt continued to serve as a convent for the Carmelites until the [[French Revolution]] of 1789.<ref name=\"moines\"/> Shortly after, Saint [[Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod]] (1782-1861), the founder of the [[Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate]], a Roman Catholic order, purchased it and used it to train young priests and re-evangelize peasants throughout Provence.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"moines\"/> Inside the church, there is a sculpture of Saint Mazenod.\n\nIt has been listed as a [[monument historique]] since 1911.<ref name=\"tourism\"/>\n\n==At present==\nIt serves as the international home of the Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate.<ref name=\"moines\"/> It is served by four priests and one brother.<ref name=\"moines\"/> Mass is said every weekday at 7am, and on Sundays at 9am and 11am.<ref name=\"moines\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Gallery\n|title=Chapel of the Oblates\n|width=160 |height=170 |lines=4\n|align=center\n|File:Chapelle Oblats Malost.JPG|\n alt1=Inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n|File:Chapelle des Oblats by Malost.JPG|\n alt2=Ceiling inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Ceiling inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n|File:Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod Oblats by Malost.JPG|\n alt3=Statue of Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Statue of Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|43.5268|5.4521|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chapel of the Oblates}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Aix-en-Provence]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic chapels in France]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Aix-en-Provence]]\n[[Category:Carmelite churches]]\n[[Category:Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n| name                 =Chapel of the Oblates\n| fullname             =\n| image                =Chapelle des Oblats (Aix-en-Provence) by Malost.JPG\n| imagesize            =\n| landscape            =\n| caption              = Facade of the Chapel of the Oblates\n| location             = Place Forbin<br/>[[Aix-en-Provence]]<br/>[[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]], [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]]\n| country              = France\n| coordinates          =\n| denomination         =[[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| tradition            =\n| membership           =\n| attendance           =\n| website              = \n| former name          =\n| bull date            =\n| founded date         =\n| founder              =\n| dedication           =\n| dedicated date       =\n| consecrated date     =\n| cult                 =\n| relics               =\n| events               =\n| past bishop          =\n| people               =\n| status               =\n| functional status    =\n| heritage designation =[[Monument historique]]\n| designated date      =\n| architect            =[[Thomas Veyrier]]<br/>[[Laurent Vallon]]\n| architectural type   =[[church architecture|church]]\n| style                =\n| groundbreaking       =\n| completed date       =1701\n| construction cost    =\n| closed date          =\n| demolished date      =\n| parish               =\n| deanery              =\n| archdeaconry         =[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aix]]\n| diocese              =\n| province             =\n| presbytery           =\n| synod                =\n| circuit              =\n| district             =\n| division             = \n| subdivision          =\n| archbishop           =[[Christophe Dufour]]\n| bishop               = \n| dean                 =\n| subdean              =\n| provost              =\n| provost-rector       =\n| viceprovost          =\n| canon                =\n| canonpastor          =\n| precentor            =\n| archdeacon           =\n| prebendary           =\n| rector               =\n| vicar                =\n| curate               =\n| priest               = \n| pastor               = \n| asstpriest           =\n| minister             =\n| assistant            =\n| honpriest            =\n| deacon               =\n| deaconness           =\n| seniorpastor         =\n| abbot                =\n| chaplain             =\n| reader               =\n| organistdom          =\n| director             =\n| organist             =\n| organscholar         =\n| chapterclerk         =\n| laychapter           =\n| warden               =\n| flowerguild          =\n| musicgroup           =\n| parishadmin          =\n| serversguild         =\n| logo                 =\n| logosize             =\n}}\nThe '''Chapel of the Oblates''' (fr: \"Chapelle des Oblats\") is a [[Roman Catholic]] chapel in [[Aix-en-Provence]]. \n\n==Location==\nIt is located on the Place Forbin, at the top of the [[Cours Mirabeau]].<ref name=\"tourism\">[http://www.aixenprovence.fr/Chapelle-des-Oblats Aix-en-Provence Tourism: Chapelle des Oblats]</ref><ref name=\"official\">[http://oblats.aix.pagesperso-orange.fr/ Official website]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe chapel was built on a former convent for the [[Carmelites]], a Roman Catholic order, built in 1625.<ref name=\"tourism\"/><ref name=\"moines\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.moinesdiocesains-aix.cef.fr/dans-la-ville/les-peres-oblats.html |title=Moines |access-date=2013-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225110225/http://www.moinesdiocesains-aix.cef.fr/dans-la-ville/les-peres-oblats.html |archive-date=2013-12-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The new chapel building was designed by [[Thomas Veyrier]] (1658-1736) and constructed from 1695 to 1701.<ref name=\"tourism\"/> The facade was designed by [[Laurent Vallon]] (1652-1724) in 1697.<ref name=\"tourism\"/> \n\nIt continued to serve as a convent for the Carmelites until the [[French Revolution]] of 1789.<ref name=\"moines\"/> Shortly after, Saint [[Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod]] (1782-1861), the founder of the [[Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate]], a Roman Catholic order, purchased it and used it to train young priests and re-evangelize peasants throughout Provence.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"moines\"/> Inside the church, there is a sculpture of Saint Mazenod.\n\nIt has been listed as a [[monument historique]] since 1911.<ref name=\"tourism\"/>\n\n==At present==\nIt serves as the international home of the Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate.<ref name=\"moines\"/> It is served by four priests and one brother.<ref name=\"moines\"/> Mass is said every weekday at 7am, and on Sundays at 9am and 11am.<ref name=\"moines\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Gallery\n|title=Chapel of the Oblates\n|width=160 |height=170 |lines=4\n|align=center\n|File:Chapelle Oblats Malost.JPG|\n alt1=Inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n|File:Chapelle des Oblats by Malost.JPG|\n alt2=Ceiling inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Ceiling inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n|File:Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod Oblats by Malost.JPG|\n alt3=Statue of Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n |Statue of Eug\u00e8ne de Mazenod inside the Chapel of the Oblates\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|43.5268|5.4521|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chapel of the Oblates}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Aix-en-Provence]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic chapels in France]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Aix-en-Provence]]\n[[Category:Carmelite churches]]\n[[Category:Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate]]\n", "name_user": "Nowolipki", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(new website)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chapel_of_the_Oblates"}
{"title_page": "Kim Won-hong", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1945|07|17|df=yes}}\n|nationality=North Korean\n|occupation=Military officer\n|birth_place={{Nowrap|[[North Hwanghae Province|North Hwanghae]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese Korea]]}}\n}}\n'''Kim Won-hong''' ({{Lang-ko|\uae40\uc6d0\ud64d}}; born 17 July 1945) is a [[North Korea]]n politician and military general.\n==Early life and education==\nKim was born in what is now North Korea's North Hwanghae Province. He graduated from the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]'s Kim Il-sung Higher Party School and has been serving in the [[Korean People's Army]] since 1962, holding several positions in the army's [[KPA General Political Bureau|General Political Bureau]] as well as commander of army corps. His first public mention was as a funeral committee member for late Marshal [[Choe Kwang]] in 1997. He was elected deputy to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref>\n==Career==\nKim Won-hong rose to prominence in 2003, as he was appointed commander of the [[Military Security Command]] (the North Korean army's intelligence unit) following the death of General [[Won Ung-hui]], who had been heading it since 1990. In April 2009, Kim was promoted to General and then migrated to the KPA General Political Bureau's Organisation Department, at the same time when [[Kim Jong-il]] reportedly put [[Kim Jong-un]] in charge of the [[State Security Department|Ministry of State Security]] to which the Military Security Command is affiliated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kim Jong-il's Son 'Effectively Control Security Forces|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/04/13/2011041300546.html|newspaper=Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=13 April 2011}}</ref> Kim was also made a member of the Party's [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] and [[Central Military Commission (DPRK)|Central Military Commission]] in September 2010 and was reported to having a role in ensuring Kim Jong-un's succession.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter Kim Jong-il's death and acting head of State Security [[U Tong-chuk]]'s purge, Kim Won-hong appeared as one of [[Kim Jong-un]]'s most trusted and supporting generals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NSA On the Edge|url=http://sinonk.com/2012/04/24/nsa-on-the-edge/|publisher=[[Sino-NK]]|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=24 April 2012}}</ref> He was made a [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] member as well as the first minister of State Security in 25 years in April 2012. He was also elected [[member of the National Defence Commission]]. The South Korean government reported in February 2017 that Kim Won-hong was fired in mid-January after he was demoted to a one-star general from a four-star one on charges of corruption and abuse of power.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sang-Hun|first1=Choe|title=North Korean Leader\u2019s Top Enforcer Is Now the One Getting Purged|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/03/world/asia/north-korea-purge-kim-jong-un-kim-won-hong.html|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The New York Times|date=4 February 2017}}</ref> He then disappeared from public view, but resurfaced in April 2017 for [[Day of the Sun]] celebrations, bearing the four-star insignia on his uniform.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Choe Sang-Hun|last2=Sanger|first2=David E.|last3=Broad|first3=William J.|title=North Korean Missile Launch Fails, and a Show of Strength Fizzles|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/asia/north-korea-missiles-pyongyang-kim-jong-un.html?_r=0|accessdate=16 April 2017|work=New York Times|date=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn late November 2017, Kim Won Hong was named as one of two North Korean officials punished for \"impure behavior.\" According to South Korean Rep. Kim Byunk-kee, Kim Won Hong, identified as deputy director of North Korea's General Political Bureau (GPB), was reportedly punished along with the director of that bureau, identified as Hwang Pyong So. The form of punishment was unspecified.<ref>Berlinger, Joshua and Taephoon, Lee. http://www.cnn.com/2017/11/21/asia/north-korea-military-punishments/index.html</ref>\n\nDespite being punished he did appear at an April 2017 parade, though when [[Kim Jong-Un]] walked by it appeared he was ignored possibly indicating he had lost some favor with him. In May 2017, he was appointed to Deputy Director of the KPA General Political Department. In September he was under investigation again and removed from the position with the WPK Organization Guidance Department. During April and May 2018, he lost his positions as WPK Political Bureau, WPK Central Military Commission and the State Affairs Commission.<ref>http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Ri Chun-su]]<br><small>[[U Tong-chuk]] as first vice-minister</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[State Security Department|Minister of State Security]]|years=2012\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jong Kyong-thaek]]}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Won Ung-hui]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commander of the Military Security Command|years=2003\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jo Kyong-chol]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Won-hong}}\n[[Category:North Korean military personnel]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:People from North Hwanghae]]\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1945|07|17|df=yes}}\n|nationality=North Korean\n|occupation=Military officer\n|birth_place={{Nowrap|[[North Hwanghae Province|North Hwanghae]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese Korea]]}}\n}}\n'''Kim Won-hong''' ({{Lang-ko|\uae40\uc6d0\ud64d}}; born 17 July 1945) is a [[North Korea]]n politician and military general.\n==Early life and education==\nKim was born in what is now North Korea's North Hwanghae Province. He graduated from the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]'s Kim Il-sung Higher Party School and has been serving in the [[Korean People's Army]] since 1962, holding several positions in the army's [[KPA General Political Bureau|General Political Bureau]] as well as commander of army corps. His first public mention was as a funeral committee member for late Marshal [[Choe Kwang]] in 1997. He was elected deputy to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref>\n==Career==\nKim Won-hong rose to prominence in 2003, as he was appointed commander of the [[Military Security Command]] (the North Korean army's intelligence unit) following the death of General [[Won Ung-hui]], who had been heading it since 1990. In April 2009, Kim was promoted to General and then migrated to the KPA General Political Bureau's Organisation Department, at the same time when [[Kim Jong-il]] reportedly put [[Kim Jong-un]] in charge of the [[State Security Department|Ministry of State Security]] to which the Military Security Command is affiliated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kim Jong-il's Son 'Effectively Control Security Forces|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/04/13/2011041300546.html|newspaper=Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=13 April 2011}}</ref> Kim was also made a member of the Party's [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] and [[Central Military Commission (DPRK)|Central Military Commission]] in September 2010 and was reported to having a role in ensuring Kim Jong-un's succession.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter Kim Jong-il's death and acting head of State Security [[U Tong-chuk]]'s purge, Kim Won-hong appeared as one of [[Kim Jong-un]]'s most trusted and supporting generals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gen. Kim Won Hong|url=http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=12 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NSA On the Edge|url=http://sinonk.com/2012/04/24/nsa-on-the-edge/|publisher=[[Sino-NK]]|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=24 April 2012}}</ref> He was made a [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] member as well as the first minister of State Security in 25 years in April 2012. He was also elected [[member of the National Defence Commission]]. The South Korean government reported in February 2017 that Kim Won-hong was fired in mid-January after he was demoted to a one-star general from a four-star one on charges of corruption and abuse of power.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sang-Hun|first1=Choe|title=North Korean Leader\u2019s Top Enforcer Is Now the One Getting Purged|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/03/world/asia/north-korea-purge-kim-jong-un-kim-won-hong.html|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The New York Times|date=4 February 2017}}</ref> He then disappeared from public view, but resurfaced in April 2017 for [[Day of the Sun]] celebrations, bearing the four-star insignia on his uniform.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Choe Sang-Hun|last2=Sanger|first2=David E.|last3=Broad|first3=William J.|title=North Korean Missile Launch Fails, and a Show of Strength Fizzles|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/asia/north-korea-missiles-pyongyang-kim-jong-un.html?_r=0|accessdate=16 April 2017|work=New York Times|date=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn late November 2017, Kim Won Hong was named as one of two North Korean officials punished for \"impure behavior.\" According to South Korean Rep. Kim Byunk-kee, Kim Won Hong, identified as deputy director of North Korea's General Political Bureau (GPB), was reportedly punished along with the director of that bureau, identified as Hwang Pyong So. The form of punishment was unspecified.<ref>Berlinger, Joshua and Taephoon, Lee. http://www.cnn.com/2017/11/21/asia/north-korea-military-punishments/index.html</ref>\n\nDespite being punished he did appear at an April 2017 parade, though when [[Kim Jong-Un]] walked by it appeared he was ignored possibly indicating he had lost some favor with him. In May 2017, he was appointed to Deputy Director of the KPA General Political Department. In September he was under investigation again and removed from the position with the WPK Organization Guidance Department. During April and May 2018, he lost his positions as WPK Political Bureau, WPK Central Military Commission and the State Affairs Commission.<ref>http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/gen-kim-won-hong/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-vac|last=[[Ri Chun-su]]<br><small>[[U Tong-chuk]] as first vice-minister</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[State Security Department|Minister of State Security]]|years=2012\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Won Ung-hui]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commander of the Military Security Command|years=2003\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jo Kyong-chol]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Won-hong}}\