{"title_page": "Astatotilapia flaviijosephi", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = VU \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | author = Freyhof, J. | year = 2014 | title = ''Haplochromis flaviijosephi'' | volume = 2014 | page = e.T61348A19009964 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2014-1.RLTS.T61348A19009964.en }}</ref>\n| taxon = Astatotilapia flaviijosephi\n| authority = ([[Louis Charles \u00c9mile Lortet|Lortet]], 1883)\n| synonyms = \n* ''Chromis flaviijosephi'' <small>Lortet, 1883</small>\n* ''Haplochromis flaviijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n* ''Haplochromis flavijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n* ''Tilapia flaviijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Astatotilapia flaviijosephi''''', the '''Jordan mouthbrooder''', is a  [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] species of [[freshwater fish]] in the family [[Cichlidae]] (cichlids).<ref name=IUCN/> It is found in the central [[Jordan River]] system, including [[Lake Tiberias]] (Kinneret), in [[Palestine]], [[Jordan]] and [[Syria]],<ref name=IUCN/><ref name=FishBase>{{FishBase | genus=Astatotilapia | species=flaviijosephi | month=October | year=2019}}</ref> making it the only [[haplochromine]] cichlid to naturally range outside of Africa.<ref name=Werner2004>{{cite journal | author1=Werner, N.Y. | author2=O. Mokady | year=2004 | title=Swimming out of Africa: mitochondrial DNA evidence for late Pliocene dispersal of a cichlid from Central Africa to the Levant | journal=Biological Journal of the Linnean Society | volume=82 | issue=1 | pages=103\u2013109 | doi=10.1111/j.1095-8312.2004.00321.x }}</ref><ref name=Steeves2019>{{cite web | author=Steeves, G. | year=2019 | title=Astatotilapia flaviijosephi | url=https://www.cichlid-forum.com/articles/asta_flavii_pt1.php | publisher=cichlid-forum | accessdate=3 November 2019 }}</ref> This species is too small to be of significant importance to fisheries,<ref name=Spataru1985>{{cite journal | author1=Spataru, P. | author2=M. Gophen | year=1985 | title=Food composition and feeding habits of Astatotilapia flaviijosephi (Lortet) in Lake Kinneret (Israel) | journal=Journal of Fish Biology | volume=26 | issue=5 | pages=503\u2013507 | doi=10.1111/j.1095-8649.1985.tb04290.x }}</ref> unlike the only other cichlids native to the [[Levant]], the economically important [[tilapia]]s (''[[Oreochromis aureus]]'', ''[[Nile tilapia|O. niloticus]]'', ''[[Sarotherodon galilaeus]]'', ''[[Coptodon zillii]]'' and ''[[Tristramella]]'').<ref name=Werner2004/><ref name=Shapiro1997>{{cite journal | author1=Shapiro, J. | author2=Z. Snovsky | year=1997 | title=The effect of the 1991/1992 winter upon the fishing industry of Lake Kinneret, Israel | journal=Fisheries Management and Ecology | volume=4 | issue=3 | pages=249\u2013252 | doi=10.1046/j.1365-2400.1997.00122.x }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''flaviijosephi'' refers to the historian [[Titus Flavius Josephus]] (37\u2013c. 100 [[Common Era|CE]]).<ref name = ETYFish>{{cite web | url = http://www.etyfish.org/cichlidae2/ | title = Order CICHLIFORMES: Family CICHLIDAE: Subfamily PSEUDOCRENILABRINAE (a-g) | accessdate= 28 November 2018 | author1 = Christopher Scharpf | author2 = Kenneth J. Lazara | last-author-amp = yes | work = The ETYFish Project Fish Name Etymology Database | publisher = Christopher Scharpf and Kenneth J. Lazara | date = 22 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Habitat and conservation status==\nThe natural [[habitat]]s of ''A. flaviijosephi'' are streams, [[Spring (hydrosphere)|springs]], canals, pools and shallow waters in lakes,<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Werner2004/> especially in areas with stones or aquatic vegetation.<ref name=IUCN/><ref name=Steeves2019/> The various subpopulations are isolated from each other, with some being [[lacustrine]] and others essentially riverine.<ref name=IUCN/> The water temperature in its range vary quite significantly with season, at least from {{cvt|14|to(-)|28.5|C|F|round=0.5}},<ref name=Shapiro1997/> but aquarium studies have shown that ''A. flaviijosephi'' are almost completely inactive at the lowermost range.<ref name=Werner1976>{{cite journal | author=Werner, Y.L. | year=1976 | title=Notes on reproduction in the mouth-brooding fish Haplochromis flaviijosephi (Teleostei : Cichlidae) in the aquarium | journal=Journal of Natural History | volume=10 | issue=6 | pages=669\u2013680 | doi=10.1080/00222937600770521 }}</ref>\n\n''A. flaviijosephi'' is threatened by [[habitat loss]] caused by drought, water extraction and pollution. It may also be threatened by [[introduced species]], although they do not appear to have affected the Lake Tiberias population.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==Appearance==\n''A. flaviijosephi'' is the smallest [[cichlid]] native to its range.<ref name=Spataru1985/> It reaches up to {{cvt|12.8|cm|in|0}} in [[total length]],<ref name = FishBase/> but most adults are about {{cvt|5-8|cm|in|0}}.<ref name=Spataru1985/> Males grow larger than females.<ref name=Steeves2019/>\n\nLike many other cichlids, its colour pattern varies with sex, age and mood; some of these colour changes can occur quite rapidly.<ref name=Werner1976/> The standard pattern is overall silvery\u2013greyish to silvery\u2013[[Tan (color)|tan]] with a vertical dark or pale line below the eye. Males have a few relatively large yellow \"egg\u2013spots\" on the [[anal fin]] and a few dotty orangish lines along the side of the body. When afraid they get about ten dark grey vertical bars on their body and when breeding two horizontal stripes. The latter pattern is stronger in courting males when most markings and colours become much more intense and contrasting, with blue\u2013black underparts and a bright blue chin. Nursing females are also more contrastingly patterned than the standard breeding season pattern, but much less intense than the courting males.<ref name=Werner1976/>\n\n==Behavior==\n===Breeding===\n''A. flaviijosephi'' breeds in the spring and summer,<ref name=FishBase/> and a female is able to spawn more than once in a season.<ref name=Werner1976/> Females will already breed when {{cvt|4|cm|in}} long and males when {{cvt|5|cm|in}}.<ref name=Werner1976/> Breeding males are highly [[Territory (animal)|territorial]] and will kill another adult male if he is unable to escape, as can happen if kept in an aquarium that is too small.<ref name=Werner1976/> Like other haplochromines, ''A. flaviijosephi'' is a [[mouthbrooder]]. The eggs are laid by the female and fertilized by the male in a small pit that he has dug in the bottom (otherwise the male does not participate in the brood care). Shortly after they are picked up by the female, which broods them in her mouth.<ref name=Steeves2019/><ref name=Werner1976/> The young are released after about two-and-a-half to five weeks when they are {{cvt|0.8-1.4|cm|in}} long.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Steeves2019/><ref name=Werner1976/> Brooding time depends on water temperature; it takes about twice as long at {{cvt|20|C|F}} compared to {{cvt|27.5|C|F|0}}.<ref name=Steeves2019/><ref name=Werner1976/> Sometimes the young are allowed to return to the female and seek security in her mouth for a couple of days after the release.<ref name=Steeves2019/><ref name=Werner1976/>\n\n===Feeding===\nThis cichlid is a predator that mostly feeds on small invertebrates,<ref name=FishBase/> but also will take [[fish fry]],<ref name=Spataru1985/> tiny fish up to about half the size of the ''A. flaviijosephi'' itself and aquatic vegetation.<ref name=Werner1976/> Adult males mostly eat [[freshwater snail]]s, while females mostly eat insects and their larvae (especially [[chironomid]]s), worms and [[amphipod]]s.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Spataru1985/> This difference in diet is also reflected in differences in the teeth of the sexes.<ref name=Spataru1985/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1755013}}\n\n[[Category:Astatotilapia|flaviijosephi]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1883]]\n[[Category:Cichlid fish of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fish of Israel]]\n[[Category:Fish of Syria]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| status = VU \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | author = Freyhof, J. | year = 2014 | title = ''Haplochromis flaviijosephi'' | volume = 2014 | page = e.T61348A19009964 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2014-1.RLTS.T61348A19009964.en }}</ref>\n| taxon = Astatotilapia flaviijosephi\n| authority = ([[Louis Charles \u00c9mile Lortet|Lortet]], 1883)\n| synonyms = \n* ''Chromis flaviijosephi'' <small>Lortet, 1883</small>\n* ''Haplochromis flaviijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n* ''Haplochromis flavijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n* ''Tilapia flaviijosephi'' <small>(Lortet, 1883)</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Astatotilapia flaviijosephi''''', the '''Jordan mouthbrooder''', is a  [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] species of [[freshwater fish]] in the family [[Cichlidae]] (cichlids).<ref name=IUCN/> It is found in the central [[Jordan River]] system, including [[Lake Tiberias]] (Kinneret), in [[Israel]], [[Jordan]] and [[Syria]],<ref name=IUCN/><ref name=FishBase>{{FishBase | genus=Astatotilapia | species=flaviijosephi | month=October | year=2019}}</ref> making it the only [[haplochromine]] cichlid to naturally range outside of Africa.<ref name=Werner2004>{{cite journal | author1=Werner, N.Y. | author2=O. Mokady | year=2004 | title=Swimming out of Africa: mitochondrial DNA evidence for late Pliocene dispersal of a cichlid from Central Africa to the Levant | journal=Biological Journal of the Linnean Society | volume=82 | issue=1 | pages=103\u2013109 | doi=10.1111/j.1095-8312.2004.00321.x }}</ref><ref name=Steeves2019>{{cite web | author=Steeves, G. | year=2019 | title=Astatotilapia flaviijosephi | url=https://www.cichlid-forum.com/articles/asta_flavii_pt1.php | publisher=cichlid-forum | accessdate=3 November 2019 }}</ref> This species is too small to be of significant importance to fisheries,<ref name=Spataru1985>{{cite journal | author1=Spataru, P. | author2=M. Gophen | year=1985 | title=Food composition and feeding habits of Astatotilapia flaviijosephi (Lortet) in Lake Kinneret (Israel) | journal=Journal of Fish Biology | volume=26 | issue=5 | pages=503\u2013507 | doi=10.1111/j.1095-8649.1985.tb04290.x }}</ref> unlike the only other cichlids native to the [[Levant]], the economically important [[tilapia]]s (''[[Oreochromis aureus]]'', ''[[Nile tilapia|O. niloticus]]'', ''[[Sarotherodon galilaeus]]'', ''[[Coptodon zillii]]'' and ''[[Tristramella]]'').<ref name=Werner2004/><ref name=Shapiro1997>{{cite journal | author1=Shapiro, J. | author2=Z. Snovsky | year=1997 | title=The effect of the 1991/1992 winter upon the fishing industry of Lake Kinneret, Israel | journal=Fisheries Management and Ecology | volume=4 | issue=3 | pages=249\u2013252 | doi=10.1046/j.1365-2400.1997.00122.x }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''flaviijosephi'' refers to the historian [[Titus Flavius Josephus]] (37\u2013c. 100 [[Common Era|CE]]).<ref name = ETYFish>{{cite web | url = http://www.etyfish.org/cichlidae2/ | title = Order CICHLIFORMES: Family CICHLIDAE: Subfamily PSEUDOCRENILABRINAE (a-g) | accessdate= 28 November 2018 | author1 = Christopher Scharpf | author2 = Kenneth J. Lazara | last-author-amp = yes | work = The ETYFish Project Fish Name Etymology Database | publisher = Christopher Scharpf and Kenneth J. Lazara | date = 22 July 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Habitat and conservation status==\nThe natural [[habitat]]s of ''A. flaviijosephi'' are streams, [[Spring (hydrosphere)|springs]], canals, pools and shallow waters in lakes,<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Werner2004/> especially in areas with stones or aquatic vegetation.<ref name=IUCN/><ref name=Steeves2019/> The various subpopulations are isolated from each other, with some being [[lacustrine]] and others essentially riverine.<ref name=IUCN/> The water temperature in its range vary quite significantly with season, at least from {{cvt|14|to(-)|28.5|C|F|round=0.5}},<ref name=Shapiro1997/> but aquarium studies have shown that ''A. flaviijosephi'' are almost completely inactive at the lowermost range.<ref name=Werner1976>{{cite journal | author=Werner, Y.L. | year=1976 | title=Notes on reproduction in the mouth-brooding fish Haplochromis flaviijosephi (Teleostei : Cichlidae) in the aquarium | journal=Journal of Natural History | volume=10 | issue=6 | pages=669\u2013680 | doi=10.1080/00222937600770521 }}</ref>\n\n''A. flaviijosephi'' is threatened by [[habitat loss]] caused by drought, water extraction and pollution. It may also be threatened by [[introduced species]], although they do not appear to have affected the Lake Tiberias population.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==Appearance==\n''A. flaviijosephi'' is the smallest [[cichlid]] native to its range.<ref name=Spataru1985/> It reaches up to {{cvt|12.8|cm|in|0}} in [[total length]],<ref name = FishBase/> but most adults are about {{cvt|5-8|cm|in|0}}.<ref name=Spataru1985/> Males grow larger than females.<ref name=Steeves2019/>\n\nLike many other cichlids, its colour pattern varies with sex, age and mood; some of these colour changes can occur quite rapidly.<ref name=Werner1976/> The standard pattern is overall silvery\u2013greyish to silvery\u2013[[Tan (color)|tan]] with a vertical dark or pale line below the eye. Males have a few relatively large yellow \"egg\u2013spots\" on the [[anal fin]] and a few dotty orangish lines along the side of the body. When afraid they get about ten dark grey vertical bars on their body and when breeding two horizontal stripes. The latter pattern is stronger in courting males when most markings and colours become much more intense and contrasting, with blue\u2013black underparts and a bright blue chin. Nursing females are also more contrastingly patterned than the standard breeding season pattern, but much less intense than the courting males.<ref name=Werner1976/>\n\n==Behavior==\n===Breeding